You need two pieces: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on the page

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- rest of your form -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

### 2. Guard the hardware/swipe back too

The custom button handles taps, but users can also swipe back or use the hardware back button. Guard that in `AppShell`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation (Pop)
    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    // Check if the current page is EditProductPage
    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        // Must get deferral BEFORE any await
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`GetDeferral()`** — must be called *before* `await`; otherwise the navigation completes before your dialog finishes.
- **`args.Cancel()`** — stops the navigation if the user picks "Stay".
- **`deferral.Complete()`** — always call this to release the deferral, whether you cancelled or not.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the custom button tap; `OnNavigating` handles swipe/hardware back.

To avoid showing the dialog twice (once from the button command, once from `OnNavigating`), set a flag like `IsNavigatingAway = true` in the `CancelCommand` before calling `GoToAsync("..")`, and check it in the guard.
